{"title_page": "Robert Alstead", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Robert Alstead.jpg|thumb|Robert Alstead]]\n'''Robert Alstead'''  {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|JP}} (23 October 1873 \u2013 9 September 1946) was a self-made businessman in the clothing trade and a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician in the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n==Family and education==\nAlstead was born in [[Upholland]], [[Lancashire]], the son of a joiner and carpenter. He was educated at [[Wigan]] Elementary School and Wigan Mining Technical College.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1896, he married Sarah Ann Deakin of Wigan.<ref>''Lady\u2019s Who Who: a List of Names of Those Women who Play a Prominent Part in Society, Art, the Professions, Business, Etc''. Pallas Pub. Co., 1938 p22</ref> He and his wife had 7 children, 6 boys and a girl.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAlstead started life as a newsboy on a railway book stall at the age of 10.<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1929''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003 p70</ref>  He became a self-made businessman. He was a sauce and pickle manufacturer in the 1890s, then moved into the clothing trade, eventually owning a chain of shops tailoring for men in the Wigan area and founding Robert Alstead, Ltd, woollen manufacturers and clothing manufacturers.<ref>Who was Who, OUP 2007</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Local politics===\n\nAlstead was an elected member of Wigan Town Council from 1913\u20131929 and was [[Mayor of Wigan]] in 1926\u201327. He was a [[School governor|governor]] of Wigan Grammar School and a governor of the Wigan Mining Technical College between 1913\u20131932. He also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref>Who was Who, OUP 2007</ref>\n\n===Parliament===\nAlstead unsuccessfully contested the [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan parliamentary constituency]] at the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]].\n\nHe next contested [[Altrincham (UK Parliament constituency)|Altrincham]] in [[Cheshire]] at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]]. The Liberals had not contested Altrincham at the previous election in 1918 when a Labour candidate challenged the sitting Unionist. Despite this disadvantage, Alstead was easily able to push the Labour candidate into third place;\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1922 United Kingdom general election|General election 1922]]\nElectorate   45,085\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Sir George Hamilton, 1st Baronet|Sir Collingwood George Clements Hamilton]]\n|votes  = 19,361\n|percentage  = 53.8\n|change  = -18.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 11,692\n|percentage  = 32.5\n|change  = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[George Benson (politician)|George Benson]]\n|votes  = 4,930\n|percentage  = 13.7\n|change  = -13.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 7,669\n|percentage  = 21.3\n|change  = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 35,983\n|percentage  = 79.8\n|change  = +11.3\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nAnother General Election took place a year later, fought on the issue of Free trade v Protectionism. Across the country there was a swing away from the Unionists and in Altrincham this helped Alstead, as the only challenger, to take the seat. He was the first Liberal to win Altrincham since January 1910.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1923 United Kingdom general election|General election 1923]]\nElectorate  45,871\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 19,046\n|percentage  = 54.2\n|change  = +21.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Sir George Hamilton, 1st Baronet|Sir Collingwood George Clements Hamilton]]\n|votes  = 16,081\n|percentage  = 45.8\n|change  = -8.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 2,965\n|percentage  = 8.4\n|change  = 29.7\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 35,127\n|percentage  = 76.6\n|change  = -3.2\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n|loser      =  Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = +14.9\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nWith only a Labour minority government in office, another General Election was called a year later. With the Unionists regaining ground across the country, Alstead was defeated at Altrincham.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1924 United Kingdom general election|General election 1924]]\nElectorate   47,253\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Cyril Atkinson]]\n|votes  = 24,439\n|percentage  = 61.0\n|change  = +15.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 15,654\n|percentage  = 39.0\n|change  = -15.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 8,785\n|percentage  = 22.0\n|change  = 30.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 40,093\n|percentage  = 84.8\n|change  = +8.2\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n|loser      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|swing      = +15.2\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nAfter 4 years of Unionist majority government which included a General Strike, the Liberal Party, now led by David Lloyd George, were challenging strongly again and Alstead had hopes of regaining Altrincham. However, this time, Alstead faced a Labour candidate as well as a Unionist, making winning the seat too difficult. \n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1929 United Kingdom general election|General election 1929]]\nElectorate   69,607\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Cyril Atkinson]]\n|votes  = 28,512\n|percentage  = 50.7\n|change  = -10.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 18,475\n|percentage  = 32.9\n|change  = -6.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Alfred Dobbs|Alfred James Dobbs]]\n|votes  = 9,242\n|percentage  = 16.4\n|change  = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 10,037\n|percentage  = 17.8\n|change  = -4.2\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 56,229\n|percentage  = 80.8\n|change  = -4.0\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = -2.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nHe did not contest the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]], when Atkinson was returned unopposed as a supporter of the National Government. Alstead did not stand for Parliament again, although he was prospective Liberal candidate for [[Preston (UK Parliament constituency)|Preston]] in 1934\u20131935, but pulled out the month before the [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935 election]].<ref>''The Times'', 25 October 1935, p16</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHe received the [[Order of the British Empire]] in the 1939 New Year's Honours List.<ref>http://www.wiganworld.co.uk/stuff/chronology10.php?opt=chrono&yr=1939</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAlstead died at [[Gathurst]], near Wigan, on 9 September 1946, aged 72 years.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-robert-alstead | Robert Alstead }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[