Wigan area and founding Robert Alstead, Ltd, woollen manufacturers and clothing manufacturers.<ref>Who was Who, OUP 2007</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Local politics===\n\nAlstead was an elected member of Wigan Town Council from 1913\u20131929 and was [[Mayor of Wigan]] in 1926\u201327. He was a [[School governor|governor]] of Wigan Grammar School and a governor of the Wigan Mining Technical College between 1913\u20131932. He also served as a [[Justice of the Peace]].<ref>Who was Who, OUP 2007</ref>\n\n===Parliament===\nAlstead unsuccessfully contested the [[Wigan (UK Parliament constituency)|Wigan parliamentary constituency]] at the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]].\n\nHe next contested [[Altrincham (UK Parliament constituency)|Altrincham]] in [[Cheshire]] at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]]. The Liberals had not contested Altrincham at the previous election in 1918 when a Labour candidate challenged the sitting Unionist. Despite this disadvantage, Alstead was easily able to push the Labour candidate into third place;\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1922 United Kingdom general election|General election 1922]]\nElectorate   45,085\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Sir George Hamilton, 1st Baronet|Sir Collingwood George Clements Hamilton]]\n|votes  = 19,361\n|percentage  = 53.8\n|change  = -18.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 11,692\n|percentage  = 32.5\n|change  = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[George Benson (politician)|George Benson]]\n|votes  = 4,930\n|percentage  = 13.7\n|change  = -13.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 7,669\n|percentage  = 21.3\n|change  = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 35,983\n|percentage  = 79.8\n|change  = +11.3\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nAnother General Election took place a year later, fought on the issue of Free trade v Protectionism. Across the country there was a swing away from the Unionists and in Altrincham this helped Alstead, as the only challenger, to take the seat. He was the first Liberal to win Altrincham since January 1910.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1923 United Kingdom general election|General election 1923]]\nElectorate  45,871\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 19,046\n|percentage  = 54.2\n|change  = +21.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Sir George Hamilton, 1st Baronet|Sir Collingwood George Clements Hamilton]]\n|votes  = 16,081\n|percentage  = 45.8\n|change  = -8.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 2,965\n|percentage  = 8.4\n|change  = 29.7\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 35,127\n|percentage  = 76.6\n|change  = -3.2\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n|winner     = Liberal Party (UK)\n|loser      =  Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = +14.9\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nWith only a Labour minority government in office, another General Election was called a year later. With the Unionists regaining ground across the country, Alstead was defeated at Altrincham.\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1924 United Kingdom general election|General election 1924]]\nElectorate   47,253\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Cyril Atkinson]]\n|votes  = 24,439\n|percentage  = 61.0\n|change  = +15.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = Robert Alstead\n|votes  = 15,654\n|percentage  = 39.0\n|change  = -15.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 8,785\n|percentage  = 22.0\n|change  = 30.4\n}}\n{{Election b