ish Empire]] in the 1939 New Year's Honours List.<ref>http://www.wiganworld.co.uk/stuff/chronology10.php?opt=chrono&yr=1939</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAlstead died at [[Gathurst]], near Wigan, on 9 September 1946, aged 72 years.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite book |last=Craig |first=F. W. S. |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig  |title=British parliamentary election results 1918-1949 |origyear=1969 |edition= 3rd |year=1983 |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services |location=Chichester |isbn= 0-900178-06-X}}\n*{{Rayment-hc|date=March 2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-robert-alstead | Robert Alstead }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Altrincham (UK Parliament constituency)|Altrincham]]\n  | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]] \u2013 [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n  | before = Sir [[Sir George Clements Hamilton, 1st Baronet|George Clements Hamilton]]\n  | after  = [[Cyril Atkinson]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alstead, Robert}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:Politics of Cheshire]]\n[[Category:People from Up Holland]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Wigan]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliament:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1934-1935 \u2192 1934\u20131935", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Alstead"}
{"title_page": "Alkali\u2013carbonate reaction", "text_new": "{{Short description|Alkali-reaction affecting impure dolomite aggregates with formation of expansive brucite}}\nThe '''alkali\u2013carbonate reaction''' is an alteration process first suspected in the 1950's in Canada for the degradation of [[concrete]] containing [[Dolomite (rock)|dolomite]] [[Construction aggregate|aggregates]].<ref name=\"Swenson_1957a\">Swenson, E.G. (1957a) A reactive aggregate undetected by ASTM test. ASTM Bulletin, 226: 48\u201350.</ref><ref name=\"Swenson_1957b>Swenson, E.G. (1957b) Cement-aggregate reaction in concrete of a Canadian bridge. ASTM Proceedings, 57: 1043\u20131056.</ref>\n\n[[Alkali]] from the [[cement]] might react with the dolomite crystals present in the aggregate inducing the production of [[brucite]], (MgOH)<sub>2</sub>, and [[calcite]] (CaCO<sub>3</sub>). This mechanism was tentatively proposed by Swenson and Gillott (1964)<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Swenson\n| first = E.G.\n|author2=Gillott, J.E. \n| year = 1964\n| title = Alkali\u2013carbonate rock reaction\n| journal = Highway Research Record\n| volume = 45\n| pages = 21\u201340\n}}</ref> and may be written as follows:\n\n:<chem>CaMg(CO3)2 + 2 NaOH -> Mg(OH)2 + CaCO3 + Na2CO3</chem>\n\nBrucite (Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>), could be responsible for the volumetric expansion after de-dolomitisation of the aggregates, due to absorption of water. \n\nThe alkali\u2013carbonate reaction is also catalyzed by the soluble NaOH produced by the reaction of {{chem|Na|2|CO|3}} with {{chem|Ca|(OH)|2}} ([[portlandite]]) present in the hardened cement paste (HCP), therefore perpetuating the reaction indefinitely as observed by Fournier and B\u00e9rub\u00e9 (2000) and B\u00e9rub\u00e9 ''et al.'' (2005).<ref name=\"Fournier_2000\">Fournier, B., & B\u00e9rub\u00e9, M. A. (2000). Alkali-aggregate reaction in concrete: a review of basic concepts and engineering implications. Canadian Journal of Civil Engineering, 27(2), 167-191. See the chemical equations on p.&nbsp;168.</ref><ref name=\"Berube_2005\">B\u00e9rub\u00e9, M. A., Smaoui, N., Bissonnette, B., & Fournier, B. (2005). Outil d\u2019\u00e9valuation et de gestion des ouvrages d\u2019art affect\u00e9s de r\u00e9actions alcalis-silice (RAS). \u00c9tudes et Recherches en Transport, Minist\u00e8re des Transports du Qu\u00e9bec. See the chemical equations on pp.&nbsp;3-4.</ref>  \n\n:<chem>Na2CO3 + Ca(OH)2 -> CaCO3 + 2 NaOH</chem>\n\nThe sum of the two above mentioned reactions leading to the ultimate production of brucite and calcium carbonate can be written as follows: \n\n:<chem>CaMg(CO3)2 + Ca(OH)2 -> Mg(OH)2 + 2 CaCO3</chem>\n\nThe alkali-carbonate reaction is much less understood than the [[alkali-silica reaction]]. Both reactions share in common the continuous regeneration of the [[sodium hydroxide]] (NaOH) after the reaction of soluble [[sodium carbonate]] or [[sodium silicate]] with [[calcium hydroxide]], {{chem|Ca|(OH)|2}}. However, impure dolomitic aggregates also often contain [[clay]] impurities, and small amounts of [[pyrite]] ({{chem|Fe|S|2}}) and [[organic matter]]. The alkali-carbonate reaction could therefore also simply hide an alkali-silica or an alkali-silicate reaction. Anyway a chemical coupling between ACR and ASR cannot be ruled out.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alkali\u2013aggregate reaction]]\n* [[Alkali\u2013silica reaction]]\n* [[Calthemite]]: Secondary calcium carbonate deposit growing under man-made structures\n* [[Pozzolanic reaction]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cement.org/tech/cct_dur_AAR.asp Cement.org | Alkali-aggregate reaction]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alkali-carbonate reaction}}\n[[Category:Cement]]\n[[Category:Concrete]]\n[[Category:Chemical reactions]]\n[[Category:Magnesium compounds]]\n\n\n{{reaction-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Alkali-reaction affecting impure dolomite aggregates with formation of expansive brucite}}\nThe '''alkali\u2013carbonate reaction''' is an alteration process first suspected in the 1950's in Canada for the degradation of [[concrete]] containing [[Dolomite (rock)|dolomite]] [[Construction aggregate|aggregates]].<ref name=\"Swenson_1957a\">Swenson, E.G. (1957a) A reactive aggregate undetected by ASTM test. ASTM Bulletin, 226: 48\u201350.</ref><ref name=\"Swenson_1957b>Swenson, E.G. (1957b) Cement-aggregate reaction in concrete of a Canadian bridge. ASTM Proceedings, 57: 1043\u20131056.</ref>\n\n[[Alkali]] from the [[cement]] might react with the dolomite crystals present in the aggregate inducing the production of [[brucite]], (MgOH)<sub>2</sub>, and [[calcite]] (CaCO<sub>3</sub>). This mechanism was tentatively proposed by Swenson and Gillott (1964)<ref>{{Cite journal\n| last = Swenson\n| first = E.G.\n|author2=Gillott, J.E. \n| year = 1964\n| title = Alkali\u2013carbonate rock reaction\n| journal = Highway Research Record\n| volume = 45\n| pages = 21\u201340\n}}</ref> and may be written as follows:\n\n:<chem>CaMg(CO3)2 + 2 NaOH -> Mg(OH)2 + CaCO3 + Na2CO3</chem>\n\nBrucite (Mg(OH)<sub>2</sub>), could be responsible for the volumetric expansion after de-dolomitisation of the aggregates, due to absorption of water. \n\nThe alkali\u2013carbonate reaction is also catalyzed by the soluble NaOH produced by the reaction of {{chem|Na|2|CO|3}} with {{chem|Ca|(OH)|2}} ([[portlandite]]) present in the hardened cement paste (HCP), therefore perpetuating the reaction indefinitely as observed by Fournier and B\u00e9rub\u00e9 (2000) and B\u00e9rube ''et al.'' (2005).<ref name=\"Fournier_2000\">Fournier, B., & B\u00e9rub\u00e9, M. A. (2000). Alkali-aggregate reaction in concrete: a review of basic concepts and engineering implications. Canadian Journal of Civil Engineering, 27(2), 167-191. See the chemical equations on p.&nbsp;168.</ref><ref name=\"Berube_2005\">B\u00e9rub\u00e9, M. A., Smaoui, N., Bissonnette, B., & Fournier, B. (2005). Outil d\u2019\u00e9valuation et de gestion des ouvrages d\u2019art affect\u00e9s de r\u00e9actions alcalis-silice (RAS). \u00c9tudes et Recherches en Transport, Minist\u00e8re des Transports du Qu\u00e9bec. See the chemical equations on pp.&nbsp;3-4.</ref>  \n\n:<chem>Na2CO3 + Ca(OH)2 -> CaCO3 + 2 NaOH</chem>\n\nThe sum of the two above mentioned reactions leading to the ultimate production of brucite and calcium carbonate can be written as follows: \n\n:<chem>CaMg(CO3)2 + Ca(OH)2 -> Mg(OH)2 + 2 CaCO3</chem>\n\nThe alkali-carbonate reaction is much less understood than the [[alkali-silica reaction]]. Both reactions share in common the continuous regeneration of the [[sodium hydroxide]] (NaOH) after the reaction of soluble [[sodium carbonate]] or [[sodium silicate]] with [[calcium hydroxide]], {{chem|Ca|(OH)|2}}. However, impure dolomitic aggregates also often contain [[clay]] impurities, and small amounts of [[pyrite]] ({{chem|Fe|S|2}}) and [[organic matter]]. The alkali-carbonate reaction could therefore also simply hide an alkali-silica or an alkali-silicate reaction. Anyway a chemical coupling between ACR and ASR cannot be ruled out.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alkali\u2013aggregate reaction]]\n* [[Alkali\u2013silica reaction]]\n* [[Calthemite]]: Secondary calcium carbonate deposit growing under man-made structures\n* [[Pozzolanic reaction]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cement.org/tech/cct_dur_AAR.asp Cement.org | Alkali-aggregate reaction]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alkali-carbonate reaction}}\n[[Category:Cement]]\n[[Category:Concrete]]\n[[Category:Chemical reactions]]\n[[Category:Magnesium compounds]]\n\n\n{{reaction-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shinkolobwe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alkali%E2%80%93carbonate_reaction"}
{"title_page": "Ronald Wilberforce Allen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:1928 Ronald Wilberforce Allen.jpg|thumb|Ronald Wilberforce Allen]]\n[[Knight Bachelor|Sir]] '''Ronald Wilberforce Allen''' (24 November 1889 \u2013 10 August 1936) was an English lawyer and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family and education==\nAllen was born in [[Stamford Hill]] in north London, the son of the Reverend William Allen, a [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan]] minister. He was educated at [[Scarborough College]] and [[King's College London|King's College, London]] where obtained his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree in 1910. He never married.<ref>''Who was Who,'' OUP 2007</ref> In religion he followed his father's path and became a prominent [[Methodist]] layman.<ref>The Times, 24 July 1923 p8</ref><ref>The Times,16 August 1929 p7</ref><ref>The Times, 21 July 1934 p7</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAllen went in for the law and was admitted as a [[solicitor]] in 1913 <ref>''The Law Journal'', Volume 82, 1936 p123, E B Ince publishers</ref> later rising to become senior partner in the firm of Wilberforce Allen & Bryant, with offices in the [[Strand, London|Strand]], [[Cheapside]] and [[Ludgate Hill]].<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Volume 80, pt. 2, 1936 p658</ref> During the First World War he served as a [[Sub-Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]]. He also gave lectures on literary and economic subjects and was an occasional contributor to various periodicals.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was later a member of the Board of the [[Abbey (bank)|Abbey Road Building Society]].<ref>The Times, 8 February 1924 p16</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Beginnings===\n\nAllen was elected as a member of [[St Albans]] City Council in 1920 and served until 1923.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1922 he was adopted as prospective Liberal candidate for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]] <ref>The Times, 31 March 1920 p16</ref> but never fought the seat.\n\n===Leicester East by-election===\n\nAllen did not contest St Albans because he was selected instead to stand as Liberal candidate at a [[by-election]] in [[Leicester East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester East]] in March 1922. The election was caused by the appointment of the Coalition Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]] as [[Lord Chief Justice of England]]. As result Hewart took a seat in the [[House of Lords]].  Allen stood as an Independent [[H H Asquith|Asquithian]] Liberal in a three-cornered contest with the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and a Coalition Liberal. The anti-socialist vote thus split, Labour's [[Alderman]] George Banton was elected with over 50% of the poll.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p166</ref>\n\n===The General Election of 1922===\n\nThe [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] followed a few months later in November and this time Allen was chosen to fight in [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]. In a straight fight with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]  he narrowly missed being elected, the majority of his opponent, William Reynolds, being only 109 (or 0.4% of the vote).<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p167</ref>\n\n===The General Elections of 1923 and 1924===\n\nHowever Allen was successful at South Leicester in the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]]. Again facing Reynolds in a straight fight he achieved a majority of 4,018 votes. He only served as the MP for a year though, as in [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]] the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] fielded a candidate. This had the effect of splitting the anti-Tory vote and Allen fell to the bottom of the poll, the Tory [[Charles Waterhouse (English politician)|Charles Waterhouse]] re-gaining the seat for his party.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p167</ref>\n\n===1929-1935===\n\nAllen tried to re-enter the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 general election]] but he had switched seats and now contested the [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury or North Division]] of [[Oxfordshire]]. In a three-cornered contest he put in a strong showing, cutting the Unionist majority from 6,228 to 2,644 with Labour in third place but he could not remove the sitting [[Tory]] MP [[Albert Edmondson, 1st Baron Sandford|A J Edmondson]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1929''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003 p98</ref>\n\nAllen did not stand as a candidate at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]] but made one last attempt to re-enter Parliament in [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935]]. He was selected to fight the seat of [[Penryn and Falmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn and Falmouth]] in [[Cornwall]] <ref>[[Garry Tregidga]], ''The Liberal Party in south-west Britain since 1918: political decline, dormancy and rebirth''; University of Exeter Press, 2000 p68</ref> which had been Liberal in 1923 and 1929 but which had been gained for the Conservatives by [[Maurice Petherick]] at the 1931 election. In a three-cornered contest the seat was retained by Petherick (39% of the vote) with the Labour candidate and historian [[A.L.Rowse]] coming second (32%) and Allen in third (28%).<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p313</ref>\n\n==Other appointments and honours==\nAllen was a member of the Delegacy of [[King's College London]] the governing body of the College. The Delegacy was a committee of the Senate of the [[University of London]], which had to ratify all major decisions.<ref>http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/6/845.htm</ref> He also served Treasurer of the [[temperance movement|Temperance]] Council of Christian Churches and was President of the London Division of the National Commercial Temperance League <ref>The Times, 20 May 1933 p9</ref> He was for a time a member of the [[Board of Governors]] of his old school, Scarborough College.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was knighted in 1932.<ref>The Times, 23 June 1932 p15</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAllen died on 10 August 1936 while on a seaside holiday in [[Fife]] shortly after completing a swim.<ref>The Times, 12 August 1936 p12</ref> He was 46 years old.<ref>http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons2.htm</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n\n* ''Methodism and Modern World Problems'' - Methuen & Co., London 1926\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]\n  | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n  | before = [[William George Waterhouse Reynolds]]\n  | after  = [[Charles Waterhouse (British politician)|Charles Waterhouse]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Ronald Wilberforce}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:People from Stamford Hill]]\n[[Category:Politics of Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:English Methodists]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War I]]\n[[Category:People educated at Scarborough College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:1928 Ronald Wilberforce Allen.jpg|thumb|Ronald Wilberforce Allen]]\n[[Knight Bachelor|Sir]] '''Ronald Wilberforce Allen''' (24 November 1889 \u2013 10 August 1936) was an English lawyer and [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician.\n\n==Family and education==\nAllen was born in [[Stamford Hill]] in north London, the son of the Reverend William Allen, a [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan]] minister. He was educated at [[Scarborough College]] and [[King's College London|King\u2019s College, London]] where obtained his [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree in 1910. He never married.<ref>''Who was Who,'' OUP 2007</ref> In religion he followed his father\u2019s path and became a prominent [[Methodist]] layman.<ref>The Times, 24 July 1923 p8</ref><ref>The Times,16 August 1929 p7</ref><ref>The Times, 21 July 1934 p7</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAllen went in for the law and was admitted as a [[solicitor]] in 1913 <ref>''The Law Journal'', Volume 82, 1936 p123, E B Ince publishers</ref> later rising to become senior partner in the firm of Wilberforce Allen & Bryant, with offices in the [[Strand, London|Strand]], [[Cheapside]] and [[Ludgate Hill]].<ref>''The Solicitors' Journal'', Volume 80, pt. 2, 1936 p658</ref> During the First World War he served as a [[Sub-Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]]. He also gave lectures on literary and economic subjects and was an occasional contributor to various periodicals.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was later a member of the Board of the [[Abbey (bank)|Abbey Road Building Society]].<ref>The Times, 8 February 1924 p16</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Beginnings===\n\nAllen was elected as a member of [[St Albans]] City Council in 1920 and served until 1923.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> In 1922 he was adopted as prospective Liberal candidate for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]] <ref>The Times, 31 March 1920 p16</ref> but never fought the seat.\n\n===Leicester East by-election===\n\nAllen did not contest St Albans because he was selected instead to stand as Liberal candidate at a [[by-election]] in [[Leicester East (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester East]] in March 1922. The election was caused by the appointment of the Coalition Liberal [[Member of Parliament (UK)|Member of Parliament]] [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Sir Gordon Hewart]] as [[Lord Chief Justice of England]]. As result Hewart took a seat in the [[House of Lords]].  Allen stood as an Independent [[H H Asquith|Asquithian]] Liberal in a three-cornered contest with the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and a Coalition Liberal. The anti-socialist vote thus split, Labour\u2019s [[Alderman]] George Banton was elected with over 50% of the poll.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p166</ref>\n\n===The General Election of 1922===\n\nThe [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]] followed a few months later in November and this time Allen was chosen to fight in [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]. In a straight fight with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]  he narrowly missed being elected, the majority of his opponent, William Reynolds, being only 109 (or 0.4% of the vote).<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p167</ref>\n\n===The General Elections of 1923 and 1924===\n\nHowever Allen was successful at South Leicester in the [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923 general election]]. Again facing Reynolds in a straight fight he achieved a majority of 4,018 votes. He only served as the MP for a year though, as in [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924 general election]] the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] fielded a candidate. This had the effect of splitting the anti-Tory vote and Allen fell to the bottom of the poll, the Tory [[Charles Waterhouse (English politician)|Charles Waterhouse]] re-gaining the seat for his party.<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p167</ref>\n\n===1929-1935===\n\nAllen tried to re-enter the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] at the [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929 general election]] but he had switched seats and now contested the [[Banbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Banbury or North Division]] of [[Oxfordshire]]. In a three-cornered contest he put in a strong showing, cutting the Unionist majority from 6,228 to 2,644 with Labour in third place but he could not remove the sitting [[Tory]] MP [[Albert Edmondson, 1st Baron Sandford|A J Edmondson]].<ref>''The Times House of Commons 1929''; Politico\u2019s Publishing 2003 p98</ref>\n\nAllen did not stand as a candidate at the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 general election]] but made one last attempt to re-enter Parliament in [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935]]. He was selected to fight the seat of [[Penryn and Falmouth (UK Parliament constituency)|Penryn and Falmouth]] in [[Cornwall]] <ref>[[Garry Tregidga]], ''The Liberal Party in south-west Britain since 1918: political decline, dormancy and rebirth''; University of Exeter Press, 2000 p68</ref> which had been Liberal in 1923 and 1929 but which had been gained for the Conservatives by [[Maurice Petherick]] at the 1931 election. In a three-cornered contest the seat was retained by Petherick (39% of the vote) with the Labour candidate and historian [[A.L.Rowse]] coming second (32%) and Allen in third (28%).<ref>F W S Craig, ''British Parliamentary Election Results, 1919-1949''; Political Reference Publications, Glasgow, 1949 p313</ref>\n\n==Other appointments and honours==\nAllen was a member of the Delegacy of [[King's College London]] the governing body of the College. The Delegacy was a committee of the Senate of the [[University of London]], which had to ratify all major decisions.<ref>http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cats/6/845.htm</ref> He also served Treasurer of the [[temperance movement|Temperance]] Council of Christian Churches and was President of the London Division of the National Commercial Temperance League <ref>The Times, 20 May 1933 p9</ref> He was for a time a member of the [[Board of Governors]] of his old school, Scarborough College.<ref>''Who was Who'', OUP 2007</ref> He was knighted in 1932.<ref>The Times, 23 June 1932 p15</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAllen died on 10 August 1936 while on a seaside holiday in [[Fife]] shortly after completing a swim.<ref>The Times, 12 August 1936 p12</ref> He was 46 years old.<ref>http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Lcommons2.htm</ref>\n\n==Publication==\n\n* ''Methodism and Modern World Problems'' - Methuen & Co., London 1926\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Leicester South (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester South]]\n  | years  = [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n  | before = [[William George Waterhouse Reynolds]]\n  | after  = [[Charles Waterhouse (British politician)|Charles Waterhouse]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allen, Ronald Wilberforce}}\n[[Category:1889 births]]\n[[Category:1936 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:English solicitors]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:People from Stamford Hill]]\n[[Category:Politics of Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:English Methodists]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War I]]\n[[Category:People educated at Scarborough College]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Wilberforce_Allen"}
{"title_page": "Graham White (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:Graham White MP.jpg|thumb|200px|Graham White]]\n'''Henry Graham White''' (26 August 1880 \u2013 19 February 1965), known as '''Graham White''', was a radical [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nHe was the son of John Arnold White and Annie Sinclair Graham of [[Birkenhead]]. He was educated at [[Birkenhead School]] from 1891 and [[Liverpool University]].<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/577687 The English Historical Review]</ref> Jointly with his brother, Arnold, he endowed the Malcolm White Scholarship at Birkenhead School in memory of their younger brother who was killed in World War I. He also bought and gave a house known as Overdale with its grounds to the school.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Old Birkonian web-site 50 years ago\n|url=http://www.obs.org.uk/50-years-ago\n|access-date=14 September 2016\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609091317/http://www.obs.org.uk/50-years-ago\n|archive-date=9 June 2018\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe married, in 1910, Mary Irene Heath of [[Nether Stowey]], [[Somerset]]. They had two sons and one daughter. Mary died in 1962.<ref>\u2018WHITE, Rt Hon. (Henry) Graham\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U52243, accessed 28 Jan 2014]</ref> His son, John Graham-White (1913-2008), was a founder of the profession of [[clinical psychology]].<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=The Guardian - Obituary\n|date=1 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1917 he was elected a Member of Birkenhead Town Council. \nIn 1918 he was Liberal candidate for the [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]] Division of Cheshire at the General Election. He was critical of the Coalition Government for calling an election while many of those in the armed forces were still abroad and unable to take part in the election. Apart from this criticism, he was happy to call himself a supporter of [[David Lloyd George]] and the Coalition Government.<ref>The Downfall of the Liberal Party by Trevor Wilson</ref> However the Coalition Government endorsed his Unionist opponent and White came third, losing his deposit;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1918 United Kingdom general election|General election 1918]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[Alfred Bigland]]\n  |votes      =13,012\n  |percentage =64.5\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =John Finigan\n  |votes      =5,399\n  |percentage =26.7\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 1,787\n  |percentage =8.8\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =7,613\n  |percentage =37.8\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =60.7\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box win\n |winner = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1920 he was re-elected to Birkenhead Council. In 1921 he was appointed the town council's Chairman of the Higher Education Committee, serving until 1922. \nIn 1922 he stood for the second time as Liberal candidate for Birkenhead East and managed to turn third place with a lost deposit into victory;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1922 United Kingdom general election|General election 1922]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =Graham White\n  |votes      =14,690\n  |percentage =57.8\n  |change     =+49.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[Alfred Bigland]]\n  |votes      =10,745\n  |percentage =42.2\n  |change     =-22.3\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =3,945\n  |percentage =15.6\n  |change     =53.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =77.5\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = +35.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nHe stood down from Birkenhead Town Council in 1923. \nHe was a passionate internationalist and in 1923 he was elected a Member of the Executive Committee, of the [[League of Nations Union]], serving until 1924.\nIn 1923 he was re-elected to parliament with an increased majority;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1923 United Kingdom general election|General election 1923]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 15,845\n  |percentage =63.5\n  |change     =+5.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Luke Lees\n  |votes      = 9,091\n  |percentage =36.5\n  |change     =-5.7\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =6,754\n  |percentage =27.0\n  |change     =+11.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =74.1\n  |change     =-3.4\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +5.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1924 at the General election, the Labour party chose to field a candidate against him with disastrous effects, causing his defeat;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1924 United Kingdom general election|General election 1924]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[William Henry Stott]]\n  |votes      =11,328\n  |percentage =40.3\n  |change     =+3.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =Graham White\n  |votes      =9,275\n  |percentage =33.0\n  |change     =-30.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =James Coulthard\n  |votes      =7,496\n  |percentage =26.7\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =2,053\n  |percentage =7.3\n  |change     =34.3\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =81.0\n  |change     =+6.9\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Unionist Party (UK)\n |loser = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +17.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1929 he re-gained his Birkenhead East seat and returned to parliament after an absence of five years;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1929 United Kingdom general election|General election 1929]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 13,157\n  |percentage =35.9\n  |change     =+2.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Edmund Brocklebank]]\n  |votes      = 11,860\n  |percentage =32.3\n  |change     =-8.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = James Coulthard\n  |votes      = 11,654\n  |percentage =31.8\n  |change     =+5.1\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =1,297\n  |percentage =3.6\n  |change     =10.9\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =78.8\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = +5.5\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1930 he served a second term as a Member of the Executive Committee, of the League of Nations Union.\nIn 1930 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Select Committee on Private Schools.\nIn 1930 he was appointed a Member of [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Indian Round Table Conference]] in London to discuss constitutional reforms.\nUpon the formation of the National Government in 1931 he was appointed Assistant [[Postmaster General of the United Kingdom|Postmaster General]].\nIn 1931 at the General Election, the Conservatives chose not to field a candidate against him as the parties were partners in the National Government, as a result, White was comfortably re-elected;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1931 United Kingdom general election|General election 1931]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      =26,938\n  |percentage =73.2\n  |change     =+37.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = C McVey\n  |votes      =9,868\n  |percentage =26.8\n  |change     =-5.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =17,070\n  |percentage =46.4\n  |change     =+36.5\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =79.1\n  |change     =+0.3\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +21.2\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1932 he resigned from National Government office along with all the other Liberal party Ministers who followed [[Sir Herbert Samuel]].<ref>Memoirs by Viscount Samuel (1945)</ref> \nIn 1933 along with the rest of the Liberal parliamentary party he went into opposition to the National government.<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1935</ref> \nIn 1935 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Broadcasting Committee.\nIn 1935 given that the Liberals were now in opposition, the Conservatives chose to oppose him once again. however, he still managed to top the poll;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1935 United Kingdom general election|General election 1935]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 16,548\n  |percentage = 48.1\n  |change     =-25.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = S J Hill\n  |votes      = 9,854\n  |percentage = 28.6\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =  M A Mercer\n  |votes      = 8,028\n  |percentage = 23.3\n  |change     =-3.5\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 6,694\n  |percentage =19.5\n  |change     =-17.0\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =74.2\n  |change     =-4.9\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = n/a\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nIn 1935 after [[Sir Archibald Sinclair]] became Liberal party leader, he offered White the position of Liberal [[Chief Whip]] but White declined.<ref>Forty Years in and out of Parliament by Sir Percy Harris</ref>\nIn 1937 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Rent Restriction Acts Committee.\nIn 1938 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Distress for Rent Committee.\nIn 1939 another general election was anticipated and White was re-selected as the Liberal prospective candidate. There were calls for the Liberal and Labour parties to join together in a [[Popular Front (UK)|Popular Front]] to defeat the National Government. By the autumn of 1939, the Birkenhead Labour party had no candidate in the field<ref>Report of the Annual Conference, 1939</ref> and a straight fight with a Conservative was anticipated. However, due to the outbreak of war the election was postponed.\nIn 1940 he was elected a Member of the Executive Committee of the [[British Council]], a body specialising in international educational and cultural exchange.\nIn 1940 he was appointed a Member of the Select Committee on National Expenditure.\nIn 1943 he was Chairman of the Committee on Seamen's Welfare in Ports.\nIn 1945 he was appointed a member of the [[Privy Council]], thus allowing him to use the title, [[The Right Honourable]].\nIn 1945 he was one of the M.P.s who visited [[Buchenwald concentration camp]].<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1950</ref>\nIn 1945 he finally lost his seat when the country swung to the Labour party;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1945 United Kingdom general election|General election 1945]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n  |votes      = 14,790\n  |percentage = 45.5\n  |change     =+22.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 10,140\n  |percentage = 31.1\n  |change     =-17.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Frederick Newell Bucher\n  |votes      = 7,624\n  |percentage = 23.4\n  |change     =-5.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 4,650\n  |percentage =14.4\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =73.6\n  |change     =-0.6\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |loser      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |swing =+19.6\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nIn 1945 he was conferred the title of Freeman of Birkenhead.\nIn 1950 his old Birkenhead East seat was abolished with part of it going into the new [[Bebington (UK Parliament constituency)|Bebington]] constituency. White stood there as Liberal candidate but finished third;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1950 United Kingdom general election|General election 1950]]: Bebington<ref>British parliamentary election results 1950-1974, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Hendrie Oakshott, Baron Oakshott|Hendrie Oakshott]]\n  |votes      = 25,309\n  |percentage = 43.8\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n  |votes      = 22,090\n  |percentage = 38.3\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 10,324\n  |percentage = 17.9\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 3,219\n  |percentage =5.5\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =87.2\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box win\n  |winner     = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing =n/a\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nHe did not stand for parliament again.\nHe was President of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] from 1954\u201355.<ref>[http://www.portcullis.parliament.uk/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqSearch=RefNo=='WHI'&dsqCmd=Show.tcl Parliament web site]</ref>\nIn 1955 he was awarded a [[Legum Doctor|LLD]] by the University of Liverpool.\nHe was Vice-President of the Liberal Party from 1958\u201359.\nWhite also served on a number of other bodies; the executive of the [[Anti-Slavery Society]],<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1931</ref> Chairman of the British Association for Labour Legislation, Chairman of the Advisory Committee on [[War risk insurance]], a Member of Council of the [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], a Member of Council of [[Bedford College for Women]], a Member of the Council on Aliens, Chairman of Council of the  Beechcroft Settlement, a Member of the Inter-Parliamentary Association, a [[Fellow of the Royal Statistical Society]], a Member of the Masterman Committee on the political activities of Civil Servants, a Member of the Curtis Committee on the Care of Children and a member of the Board of Social Sciences and Administration of Liverpool University.<ref>\u2018WHITE, Rt Hon. (Henry) Graham\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U52243, accessed 28 Jan 2014]</ref>\n\nHis parliamentary colleague [[Sir Percy Harris, 1st Baronet|Sir Percy Harris]] described him as ''\"disinterested, with a fine sense of duty and a varied knowledge of every kind of social problem, he was a mine of information and always ready to step into the breach.\"''<ref>Forty Years in and out of Parliament by Sir Percy Harris</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nA collection of White's papers were donated to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] by his grandson and have been deposited in the [[House of Lords]] Records Office. The papers comprise political papers and correspondence including constituency and election material, papers concerning Liberal Party organisation, draft bills, committee reports and memoranda on topics such as unemployment benefit and old age pensions. There are papers on White's interests outside Parliament, including the [[British Council]] and the [http://www.eleanorrathbonetrust.org.uk/ Eleanor Rathbone Trust]. There are also papers regarding White's campaign on behalf of German internees during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-henry-white | Henry Graham White }}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?sText=Henry+Graham+White&search=ss&OConly=true&firstRun=true&LinkID=mp52633&rNo=2&role=sit Portrait of Henry Graham White]\n*Photograph of White and other MPs on their way to Buchenwald: http://find.galegroup.com/iln/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=ILN&userGroupName=esusslib&tabID=T003&docPage=article&docId=HN3100337416&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0\n*White at Buchenwald: http://www.britishpathe.com/video/german-atrocities/query/Buchenwald\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]]\n  | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n  | before = [[Alfred Bigland]]\n  | after  = [[William Henry Stott]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]]\n  | years  = [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\n  | before = [[William Henry Stott]]\n  | after  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=[[President of the Liberal Party (UK)|President of the Liberal Party]]|years=1954\u20131955|before=[[Lawrence Robson]]|after=[[Philip Rea, 2nd Baron Rea|The Lord Rea]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Henry Graham}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Liberal Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:People educated at Birkenhead School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n[[File:Graham White MP.jpg|thumb|200px|Graham White]]\n'''Henry Graham White''' (26 August 1880 \u2013 19 February 1965), known as '''Graham White''', was a radical [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] politician.\n\n==Background==\nHe was the son of John Arnold White and Annie Sinclair Graham of [[Birkenhead]]. He was educated at [[Birkenhead School]] from 1891 and [[Liverpool University]].<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/pss/577687 The English Historical Review]</ref> Jointly with his brother, Arnold, he endowed the Malcolm White Scholarship at Birkenhead School in memory of their younger brother who was killed in World War I. He also bought and gave a house known as Overdale with its grounds to the school.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Old Birkonian web-site 50 years ago\n|url=http://www.obs.org.uk/50-years-ago\n|access-date=14 September 2016\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180609091317/http://www.obs.org.uk/50-years-ago\n|archive-date=9 June 2018\n|url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe married, in 1910, Mary Irene Heath of [[Nether Stowey]], [[Somerset]]. They had two sons and one daughter. Mary died in 1962.<ref>\u2018WHITE, Rt Hon. (Henry) Graham\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U52243, accessed 28 Jan 2014]</ref> His son, John Graham-White (1913-2008), was a founder of the profession of [[clinical psychology]].<ref>{{cite journal\n|title=The Guardian - Obituary\n|date=1 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1917 he was elected a Member of Birkenhead Town Council. \nIn 1918 he was Liberal candidate for the [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]] Division of Cheshire at the General Election. He was critical of the Coalition Government for calling an election while many of those in the armed forces were still abroad and unable to take part in the election. Apart from this criticism, he was happy to call himself a supporter of [[David Lloyd George]] and the Coalition Government.<ref>The Downfall of the Liberal Party by Trevor Wilson</ref> However the Coalition Government endorsed his Unionist opponent and White came third, losing his deposit;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1918 United Kingdom general election|General election 1918]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[Alfred Bigland]]\n  |votes      =13,012\n  |percentage =64.5\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =John Finigan\n  |votes      =5,399\n  |percentage =26.7\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 1,787\n  |percentage =8.8\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =7,613\n  |percentage =37.8\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =60.7\n  |change     = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box win\n |winner = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = n/a\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1920 he was re-elected to Birkenhead Council. In 1921 he was appointed the town council's Chairman of the Higher Education Committee, serving until 1922. \nIn 1922 he stood for the second time as Liberal candidate for Birkenhead East and managed to turn third place with a lost deposit into victory;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1922 United Kingdom general election|General election 1922]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =Graham White\n  |votes      =14,690\n  |percentage =57.8\n  |change     =+49.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[Alfred Bigland]]\n  |votes      =10,745\n  |percentage =42.2\n  |change     =-22.3\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =3,945\n  |percentage =15.6\n  |change     =53.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =77.5\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = +35.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nHe stood down from Birkenhead Town Council in 1923. \nHe was a passionate internationalist and in 1923 he was elected a Member of the Executive Committee, of the [[League of Nations Union]], serving until 1924.\nIn 1923 he was re-elected to parliament with an increased majority;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1923 United Kingdom general election|General election 1923]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 15,845\n  |percentage =63.5\n  |change     =+5.7\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Luke Lees\n  |votes      = 9,091\n  |percentage =36.5\n  |change     =-5.7\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =6,754\n  |percentage =27.0\n  |change     =+11.4\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =74.1\n  |change     =-3.4\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +5.7\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1924 at the General election, the Labour party chose to field a candidate against him with disastrous effects, causing his defeat;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1924 United Kingdom general election|General election 1924]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =[[William Henry Stott]]\n  |votes      =11,328\n  |percentage =40.3\n  |change     =+3.8\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =Graham White\n  |votes      =9,275\n  |percentage =33.0\n  |change     =-30.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =James Coulthard\n  |votes      =7,496\n  |percentage =26.7\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =2,053\n  |percentage =7.3\n  |change     =34.3\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =81.0\n  |change     =+6.9\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Unionist Party (UK)\n |loser = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +17.1\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1929 he re-gained his Birkenhead East seat and returned to parliament after an absence of five years;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1929 United Kingdom general election|General election 1929]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 13,157\n  |percentage =35.9\n  |change     =+2.9\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Edmund Brocklebank]]\n  |votes      = 11,860\n  |percentage =32.3\n  |change     =-8.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = James Coulthard\n  |votes      = 11,654\n  |percentage =31.8\n  |change     =+5.1\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =1,297\n  |percentage =3.6\n  |change     =10.9\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =78.8\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |loser = Unionist Party (UK)\n |swing = +5.5\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1930 he served a second term as a Member of the Executive Committee, of the League of Nations Union.\nIn 1930 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Select Committee on Private Schools.\nIn 1930 he was appointed a Member of [[Round Table Conferences (India)|Indian Round Table Conference]] in London to discuss constitutional reforms.\nUpon the formation of the National Government in 1931 he was appointed Assistant [[Postmaster General of the United Kingdom|Postmaster General]].\nIn 1931 at the General Election, the Conservatives chose not to field a candidate against him as the parties were partners in the National Government, as a result, White was comfortably re-elected;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1931 United Kingdom general election|General election 1931]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      =26,938\n  |percentage =73.2\n  |change     =+37.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = C McVey\n  |votes      =9,868\n  |percentage =26.8\n  |change     =-5.0\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      =17,070\n  |percentage =46.4\n  |change     =+36.5\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =79.1\n  |change     =+0.3\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = +21.2\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nIn 1932 he resigned from National Government office along with all the other Liberal party Ministers who followed [[Sir Herbert Samuel]].<ref>Memoirs by Viscount Samuel (1945)</ref> \nIn 1933 along with the rest of the Liberal parliamentary party he went into opposition to the National government.<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1935</ref> \nIn 1935 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Broadcasting Committee.\nIn 1935 given that the Liberals were now in opposition, the Conservatives chose to oppose him once again. however, he still managed to top the poll;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1935 United Kingdom general election|General election 1935]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 16,548\n  |percentage = 48.1\n  |change     =-25.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = S J Hill\n  |votes      = 9,854\n  |percentage = 28.6\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =  M A Mercer\n  |votes      = 8,028\n  |percentage = 23.3\n  |change     =-3.5\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 6,694\n  |percentage =19.5\n  |change     =-17.0\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =74.2\n  |change     =-4.9\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n |winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n |swing = n/a\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nIn 1935 after [[Sir Archibald Sinclair]] became Liberal party leader, he offered White the position of Liberal [[Chief Whip]] but White declined.<ref>Forty Years in and out of Parliament by Sir Percy Harris</ref>\nIn 1937 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Rent Restriction Acts Committee.\nIn 1938 he was appointed a Member of the parliamentary Distress for Rent Committee.\nIn 1939 another general election was anticipated and White was re-selected as the Liberal prospective candidate. There were calls for the Liberal and Labour parties to join together in a [[Popular Front (UK)|Popular Front]] to defeat the National Government. By the autumn of 1939, the Birkenhead Labour party had no candidate in the field<ref>Report of the Annual Conference, 1939</ref> and a straight fight with a Conservative was anticipated. However, due to the outbreak of war the election was postponed.\nIn 1940 he was elected a Member of the Executive Committee of the [[British Council]], a body specialising in international educational and cultural exchange.\nIn 1940 he was appointed a Member of the Select Committee on National Expenditure.\nIn 1943 he was Chairman of the Committee on Seamen\u2019s Welfare in Ports.\nIn 1945 he was appointed a member of the [[Privy Council]], thus allowing him to use the title, [[The Right Honourable]].\nIn 1945 he was one of the M.P.s who visited [[Buchenwald concentration camp]].<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1950</ref>\nIn 1945 he finally lost his seat when the country swung to the Labour party;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1945 United Kingdom general election|General election 1945]]: Birkenhead East<ref>British parliamentary election results 1918-1949, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n  |votes      = 14,790\n  |percentage = 45.5\n  |change     =+22.2\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 10,140\n  |percentage = 31.1\n  |change     =-17.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Frederick Newell Bucher\n  |votes      = 7,624\n  |percentage = 23.4\n  |change     =-5.2\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 4,650\n  |percentage =14.4\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =73.6\n  |change     =-0.6\n}}\n{{Election box gain with party link|\n  |winner     = Labour Party (UK)\n  |loser      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |swing =+19.6\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nIn 1945 he was conferred the title of Freeman of Birkenhead.\nIn 1950 his old Birkenhead East seat was abolished with part of it going into the new [[Bebington (UK Parliament constituency)|Bebington]] constituency. White stood there as Liberal candidate but finished third;\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1950 United Kingdom general election|General election 1950]]: Bebington<ref>British parliamentary election results 1950-1974, Craig, F.W.S.</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Hendrie Oakshott, Baron Oakshott|Hendrie Oakshott]]\n  |votes      = 25,309\n  |percentage = 43.8\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n  |votes      = 22,090\n  |percentage = 38.3\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Graham White\n  |votes      = 10,324\n  |percentage = 17.9\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes      = 3,219\n  |percentage =5.5\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =87.2\n  |change     =n/a\n}}\n{{Election box win\n  |winner     = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing =n/a\n}}\n{{election box end}}\nHe did not stand for parliament again.\nHe was President of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] from 1954-55.<ref>[http://www.portcullis.parliament.uk/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqDb=Catalog&dsqSearch=RefNo=='WHI'&dsqCmd=Show.tcl Parliament web site]</ref>\nIn 1955 he was awarded a [[Legum Doctor|LLD]] by the University of Liverpool.\nHe was Vice-President of the Liberal Party from 1958-59.\nWhite also served on a number of other bodies; the executive of the [[Anti-Slavery Society]],<ref>The Times House of Commons, 1931</ref> Chairman of the British Association for Labour Legislation, Chairman of the Advisory Committee on [[War risk insurance]], a Member of Council of the [[Royal Institute of International Affairs]], a Member of Council of [[Bedford College for Women]], a Member of the Council on Aliens, Chairman of Council of the  Beechcroft Settlement, a Member of the Inter-Parliamentary Association, a [[Fellow of the Royal Statistical Society]], a Member of the Masterman Committee on the political activities of Civil Servants, a Member of the Curtis Committee on the Care of Children and a member of the Board of Social Sciences and Administration of Liverpool University.<ref>\u2018WHITE, Rt Hon. (Henry) Graham\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132007; online edn, Oxford University Press, Dec 2007 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U52243, accessed 28 Jan 2014]</ref>\n\nHis parliamentary colleague [[Sir Percy Harris, 1st Baronet|Sir Percy Harris]] described him as ''\"disinterested, with a fine sense of duty and a varied knowledge of every kind of social problem, he was a mine of information and always ready to step into the breach.\"''<ref>Forty Years in and out of Parliament by Sir Percy Harris</ref>\n\n==Papers==\nA collection of White's papers were donated to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] by his grandson and have been deposited in the [[House of Lords]] Records Office. The papers comprise political papers and correspondence including constituency and election material, papers concerning Liberal Party organisation, draft bills, committee reports and memoranda on topics such as unemployment benefit and old age pensions. There are papers on White's interests outside Parliament, including the [[British Council]] and the [http://www.eleanorrathbonetrust.org.uk/ Eleanor Rathbone Trust]. There are also papers regarding White's campaign on behalf of German internees during the [[Second World War]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{hansard-contribs | mr-henry-white | Henry Graham White }}\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait.php?sText=Henry+Graham+White&search=ss&OConly=true&firstRun=true&LinkID=mp52633&rNo=2&role=sit Portrait of Henry Graham White]\n*Photograph of White and other MPs on their way to Buchenwald: http://find.galegroup.com/iln/infomark.do?&source=gale&prodId=ILN&userGroupName=esusslib&tabID=T003&docPage=article&docId=HN3100337416&type=multipage&contentSet=LTO&version=1.0\n*White at Buchenwald: http://www.britishpathe.com/video/german-atrocities/query/Buchenwald\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]]\n  | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]]\u2013[[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]]\n  | before = [[Alfred Bigland]]\n  | after  = [[William Henry Stott]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Birkenhead East (UK Parliament constituency)|Birkenhead East]]\n  | years  = [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]\u2013[[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945]]\n  | before = [[William Henry Stott]]\n  | after  = [[Frank Soskice, Baron Stow Hill|Frank Soskice]]\n}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=[[President of the Liberal Party (UK)|President of the Liberal Party]]|years=1954\u20131955|before=[[Lawrence Robson]]|after=[[Philip Rea, 2nd Baron Rea|The Lord Rea]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White, Henry Graham}}\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Liberal Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:People educated at Birkenhead School]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1954-55 \u2192 1954\u201355 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graham_White_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Kanika Kapoor", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian singer}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kanika Kapoor\n| image              = Kanika Kapoor launches \"Teddy Bear\".jpg\n| caption            = Kapoor in 2016\n| native_name        = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1978|08|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lucknow]], Uttar Pradesh, India\n| alma_mater         = [[Bhatkhande Music Institute]]\n|nationality= Indian\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|composer}}\n| years_active       = 2012\u2013present\n| awards             = [[#Awards|See below]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Western music (North America)|Western]]\n* pop\n* [[filmi]]\n* [[Sufi music|sufi]]\n}}\n| label              = {{flatlist|\n* [[Super Cassettes Industries T-Series|T-Series]]\n* [[Zee Entertainment Enterprises|Zee Music Company]]\n}}\n| instrument         = Vocals\n| website            = [https://www.kanikakapoor.com kanikakapoor.com]\n| associated_acts    = {{flatlist|\n* [[Meet Bros]]\n}}\n}}\n| signature          = \n| spouse             = {{marriage |Raj Chandok |1998 |2012 |end={{abbr|div.|divorced}}}}\n}}\n'''Kanika Kapoor'''  (born 21 August 1978) is an Indian singer. She was born and raised in [[Lucknow]]. She always aspired to pursue a career in singing, but she married businessman Raj Chandok in 1997 and moved to London, where she gave birth to three children. After getting a divorce from Raj in 2012, she relocated to [[Mumbai]] to become a singer. Kapoor's first song \"[[Alif Allah (Jugni)|Jugni Ji]]\" (2012) was for a music video{{ndash}}which became a commercial success. In 2014, she began her Bollywood playback singing career with the song \"[[Baby Doll (Kanika Kapoor song)|Baby Doll]]\" for the film ''[[Ragini MMS 2]]''. Upon its release, \"Baby Doll\" went viral and topped the charts and Kapoor received wide critical acclaim and several accolades for her singing style, including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer]].\n\nKapoor subsequently earned widespread recognition and success for singing one of the Hindi cinema's top charted songs, including \"Lovely\" and \"Kamlee\" for the film ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]'' (2014), \"[[Chittiyaan Kalaiyaan]]\" for the film  ''[[Roy (film)|Roy]]'' (2015),  \"Desi Look\" for the film ''[[Ek Paheli Leela]]'' (2015), \"Nachan Farrate\" for the film ''[[All Is Well (2015 film)|All Is Well]]'' (2015), \"Jugni Peeke Tight Hai\" for the film ''[[Kis Kisko Pyaar Karoon]]'' (2015), \"Jab Chaye Tera Jadoo\" for the film ''[[Main Aur Charles]]'' (2015), \"Neendein Khul Jaati Hain\" for the film ''[[Hate Story 3]]'' (2015), \"premika\" for the film ''[[Dilwale (2015 film)|Dilwale]]'' (2015), the later of these rank among the [[List of Bollywood highest-grossing films in overseas markets|highest-grossing Bollywood film]]. The song \"Da Da Dasse\" from the film ''[[Udta Punjab]]'' (2016), earned her several Best Playback Singer awards and nominations{{mdash}}following which she sang the songs, \"Hug Me\" from ''[[Beiimaan Love]]'' (2016), \"Luv Letter\" from the film ''[[The Legend of Michael Mishra]]'' (2016) and \"Beat Pe Booty\" from the film ''[[A Flying Jatt]]'' (2016), all of which earned her further success.\n\nIn March 2020 after returning from London, she attended few parties with Indian politicians and VIPs at Hotel Taj, Lucknow, against Government of India \u2013 Ministry of Health's home quarantine advisory against Coronavirus at the time. Subsequently, she was tested positive<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/kanika-kapoor-tests-positive-3rd-time-friend-is-negative/articleshow/74804161.cms|title=Kanika Kapoor tests positive 3rd time, friend is negative &#124; India News|website=The Times of India}}</ref> for Covid-19. A domino effect lead [[President of India]] to cancel his plans, and engagements indefinitely. A complaint was lodged against her for her negligence.\n\n==Early life==\nKapoor was born on 21 August 1978 in [[Lucknow]], Uttar Pradesh. Her father, Rajeev Kapoor, is a businessman, and her mother, Poonam Kapoor, is a boutique owner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.celenote.com/kanika-kapoor-wiki/|title=Kanika Kapoor Biography|website=celenote.com|url-status=live|access-date=17 November 2018}}</ref> She was born and brought up in a [[Khatri]] family from [[Lucknow]], Uttar Pradesh<ref name=\"TOISmallTownGirl\">{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Kanika-Kapoor-I-am-just-a-simple-small-town-girl-who-has-been-through-a-lot/articleshow/46502819.cms|title=Kanika Kapoor: I am just a simple small town girl who has been through a lot|work=The Times of India|quote=\"I am a Khatri, who was born and brought up in Lucknow ... I got married to Raj and moved to London when I was only 17 ... we separated about five years ago and finally divorced three years back ... This was January 2012 ... By July, Raj and I had separated and in October, I won the best British Asian award.\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118115911/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Kanika-Kapoor-I-am-just-a-simple-small-town-girl-who-has-been-through-a-lot/articleshow/46502819.cms?from=mdr|archivedate=18 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> where she also studied music.<ref name=\"Baby Doll\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/music/news-and-interviews/I-had-no-idea-who-Sunny-Leone-was-Baby-Doll-singer/articleshow/32791663.cms?intenttarget=no |title=I had no idea who Sunny Leone was: Baby Doll singer |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |author=Sunayana Suresh |date=18 March 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013074928/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/I-had-no-idea-who-Sunny-Leone-was-Baby-Doll-singer/articleshow/32791663.cms|archivedate=13 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/life-style/star-track/-i-love-chandigarh-sarson-ka-saag--/254019.html|title=I love Chandigarh, sarson ka saag ... |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> At the age of 12, Kapoor started to study classical music under musician Pandit Ganesh Prasad Mishra from [[Varanasi]] and was accompanied by him to classical concerts around India. Kapoor participated in many music competitions at school in her childhood. At the age of 15, she did a stint with [[All India Radio (band)|All India Radio]] and also accompanied [[bhajan]] singer [[Anup Jalota]] in his shows. She did her B.A. and then Masters in music from [[Bhatkhande Music Institute]] in Lucknow. She then moved to [[Mumbai]] to pursue her music career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/I-Am-Living-My-Ambitions-and-Dreams-Says-Kanika-Kapoor/2015/05/12/article2810357.ece|title=I Am Living My Ambitions and Dreams, Says Kanika Kapoor|work=[[The New Indian Express]]|author=R.M. Vijayakar|date=12 May 2015|accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKanika Kapoor married to Raj Chandok, an [[Non-resident Indian|NRI businessman]], in 1997 and moved to London with her husband, with whom she had three children. She separated from her husband in 2012 and moved back to her parents home in Lucknow.<ref name=\"toi45177954\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/music/Im-not-here-jut-to-sing-for-Bollywood-Kanika-Kapoor/articleshow/45177954.cms |title=Im not here jut to sing for Bollywood: Kanika Kapoor |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |author=Elina Priyadarshini Padhiary |date=18 November 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://khabar.ndtv.com/news/filmy/photos-singer-kanika-kapoor-was-married-when-she-was-18-1420557|title=PHOTOS: 18 \u0915\u0940 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u0930 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0939\u0941\u0908 \u0925\u0940 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0917\u0930 \u0915\u0928\u093f\u0915\u093e \u0915\u092a\u0942\u0930 \u0915\u0940 \u0936\u093e\u0926\u0940, 3 \u092c\u091a\u094d\u091a\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0940 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u092e\u093e\u0902|work=[[NDTV India]]|date=18 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"toi35150257\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/I-had-to-deal-with-a-lot-of-vicious-rumours-Kanika-Kapoor/articleshow/35150257.cms |title=I had to deal with a lot of vicious rumours: Kanika Kapoor |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |author=Devanshi Seth |date=15 May 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The couple divorced in 2012.<ref name=\"TOISmallTownGirl\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mumbaimirror.com/others/sunday-read/Small-talk-The-sirens-call/articleshow/50790072.cms|title=Smaal talk: The siren's call|work=[[Mumbai Mirror]]|date=30 January 2016|author=Roy, Saumya|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Kapoor, despite singing various Bollywood songs with [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] lyrics, she cannot speak Punjabi and thus considers herself a \"UP Khatri\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/music/im-not-punjabi-i-dont-know-punjabi-kanika-kapoor-2866104/|title=I'm not Punjabi, I don't know Punjabi: Kanika Kapoor|date=21 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Coronavirus infection==\nKapoor was tested positive for [[COVID-19]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] on 20 March 2020. She returned to India from London on 9 March, whereupon she later threw a party for her family and friends in [[Lucknow]].<ref>{{cite news  |title=Baby Doll singer Kanika Kapoor tests coronavirus positive. She hid travel history, threw party at 5-star |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/baby-doll-singer-kanika-kapoor-tests-coronavirus-positive-she-hid-travel-history-threw-party-at-5-star-1657811-2020-03-20 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=India Today }}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/kanika-kapoor-who-tested-positive-for-coronavirus-was-advised-home-quarantine-says-fir-she-contradic-2198282|title=Complaint Against Covid-19 Positive Singer Kanika Kapoor Raises Questions|website=NDTV.com}}</ref> Her father, Rajiv Kapoor, stated she attended three parties, which Kanika Kapoor denied. Upon Kapoor testing positive for COVID-19, and updating about it on Twitter; former chief minister of Rajasthan [[Vasundhara Raje]] stated in a tweet that herself, and her son had met Kapoor at a party, and later went in a self imposed quarantine till their reports came back as negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-vasundhara-raje-son-dushyant-singh-who-met-kanika-kapoor-at-party-test-negative-1658202-2020-03-21|title=Coronavirus in India: Vasundhara Raje, son Dushyant Singh, who met Kanika Kapoor at party, test negative|first1=Dev Ankur Wadhawan|last1=JaipurMarch 21|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 21|first3=2020 18:15|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/coronavirus-positive-kanika-kapoor-s-father-says-she-attended-3-parties-singer-denies-1657854-2020-03-20|title=Coronavirus-positive Kanika Kapoor's father says she attended 3 parties, singer denies|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiMarch 20|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 20|first3=2020 20:16|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nThe party in question was attended by several prominent personalities, and bureaucrats<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/viral-pics-kanika-kapoor-vasundhara-raje-dushyant-at-lucknow-party-1657880-2020-03-20|title=Viral pics: Kanika Kapoor, Vasundhara Raje, Dushyant at Lucknow party|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiMarch 20|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 20|first3=2020 18:30|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> including former chief minister of Rajasthan [[Vasundhara Raje]], her son \u2013 incumbent MP [[Dushyant Singh]], and Uttar Pradesh's state minister of medical, and health [[Jai Pratap Singh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-covid-19-jai-pratap-singh-kanika-kapoor-1658168-2020-03-21|title=Covid-19: UP Health Minister Jai Pratap Singh tests negative after attending party with Kanika Kapoor|first1=Press Trust of India|last1=LucknowMarch 21|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 21|first3=2020 14:51|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\n[[Dushyant Singh]] later attended [[Parliament of India]]. As the party was attended by a few politicians, a domino effect lead to the quarantine of six members of parliament, the health minister of Uttar Pradesh Jai Pratap Singh, former chief minister of Rajasthan Vasundhara Raje, two top bureaucrats in the central government, three members of the legislative assembly of UP, and other bureaucratic elites went into self-quarantine on the same day when Kapoor made her test result public.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-covid-chaos-from-lucknow-to-lutyens/story-EzgmjcfP8VPIUe0zbpbdrN.html|title=Covid chaos, from Lucknow to Lutyens: Tracing Kanika Kapoor\u2019s actions|date=21 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nDushyant Singh later also met the [[President of India]], as a result, [[Rashtrapati Bhawan]] cancelled all plans, and engagements of President of India indefinitely.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nChief medical officer lodged complaint against Kapoor. The [[First Information Report|FIR]] says:<ref name=\"auto1\"/> {{quote|[...]when the singer was screened at the Lucknow airport on March 14, \"high viral load was detected\". She was advised home quarantine, but the advice was disregarded.}} The complaint was filed under Sections 188, 269, and 270 of the Indian Penal Code.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/singer-kanika-kapoor-who-tested-postive-for-coronavirus-booked-for-negligence/articleshow/74741688.cms|title=Singer Kanika Kapoor, who tested postive for coronavirus, booked for negligence|date=21 March 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nWhile Kapoor was denying attending any social gathering, except one small family gathering, video of her playing [[holi]] with many people, and photos from the party including political elites went viral.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/bollywood/story/kanika-kapoor-says-she-was-at-1-family-dinner-not-3-parties-viral-video-from-lucknow-holi-bash-proves-otherwise-1657925-2020-03-20|title=Kanika Kapoor says she was at 1 family dinner, not 3 parties. Viral video from Lucknow Holi bash proves otherwise|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiMarch 20|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 20|first3=2020 21:17|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/music/kanika-kapoor-s-lucknow-party-pics-go-viral-after-coronavirus-diagnosis-internet-calls-her-irresponsible/story-unyHzsAcMJbxu5YPHB66HJ.html|title=Kanika Kapoor's Lucknow party pics go viral after coronavirus diagnosis, internet calls her irresponsible|date=20 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> After returning from the UK, Kapoor has attended three parties in Lucknow, one in Kanpur and has been part of at least two other public gatherings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/sona-mohapatra-attacks-kanika-kapoor-for-hiding-travel-history/articleshow/74740463.cms|title=COVID-19: Sona Mohapatra attacks Kanika Kapoor for hiding travel history|website=The Times of India}}</ref> Kapoor has been facing severe criticism on Twitter and other internet platforms for her negligence, and contradictary statements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telanganatoday.com/kanikakacoronacrime-trends-as-netizens-bash-singer-create-memes|title=#KanikaKaCoronaCrime trends as netizens bash singer, create memes|website=Telangana Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/sonam-kapoor-defends-kanika-kapoor-she-came-back-on-9th-india-wasn-t-self-isolating-but-playing-holi/story-MEPW9ce5SdlE0B5VoIG41J.html|title=Sonam Kapoor defends Kanika Kapoor: \u2018She came back on 9th. India wasn\u2019t self isolating but playing Holi\u2019|date=21 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nShe complained about the hospital facilities and later the hospital authorities stated that she didn't co-operate with the staff.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abplive.com/videos/news/corona-infected-kanika-kapoor-not-cooperating-with-lucknow-hospital-1180300|title=Corona infected Kanika Kapoor not cooperating with Lucknow hospital|date=22 March 2020|website=news.abplive.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/kanika-kapoor-tests-coronavirus-positive-second-time-1658999-2020-03-24|title=Kanika Kapoor tests coronavirus-positive second time|first1=Asian News International|last1=LucknowMarch 24|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 24|first3=2020 12:05|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> The director of the hospital stated: \"Kapoor has been provided with the best that is possible in a hospital. She must co-operate as a patient and not throw tantrums of a star [...] Utmost care is being taken but she must first start behaving as a patient and not a star.\" She received further massive criticism on internet for not co-operating with hospital staff, and for throwing tantrums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/story/kanika-kapoor-given-best-facilities-must-start-behaving-as-patient-not-star-hospital-1658300-2020-03-21|title=Kanika Kapoor must start behaving like patient, not throw tantrums like a star: Hospital|first1=Kumar Abhishek|last1=LucknowMarch 21|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 22|first3=2020 09:03|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> The test reports of 63 people out of around 300 that she interacted with, came out to be negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/entertainment/hindi/kanika-kapoor-tests-positive-again-in-second-test-for-covid-19-lucknow-police-still-tracking-singers-missing-friend/videoshow/74786308.cms|title=Kanika Kapoor tests positive again in second test for COVID-19, Lucknow police still tracking singer's missing friend &#124; Hindi Movie News \u2013 Bollywood|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/entertainment/2020/03/25/kanika-kapoor-tests-coronavirus-positive-for-third-time.html|title=Kanika Kapoor tests coronavirus positive for third time|website=The Week}}</ref> On 24 March 2020, the second COVID-2019 test which was conducted due to the doubt created in the mind of her family members, came out to be positive.<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kanika-kapoor-s-family-raises-questions-about-report-which-declared-her-covid-19-positive-1658430-2020-03-22|title=Kanika Kapoor's family raises questions about report which declared her Covid-19 positive|first1=india today digital|last1=LucknowMarch 22|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 22|first3=2020 15:32|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> She tested positive for third time on 27 March. She was previously tested on 20, and 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/kanika-kapoor-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-for-third-time/articleshow/74860841.cms|title=Kanika Kapoor tests positive for coronavirus for third time|date=28 March 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/singer-kanika-kapoor-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-for-third-time/articleshow/74851384.cms|title=Singer Kanika Kapoor tests positive for coronavirus for third time - Times of India \u25ba|website=The Times of India}}</ref> She was tested positive for the fifth consecutive time on March 31.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/entertainment/celebs/kanika-kapoor-tests-covid-19-positive-for-5th-time-doctors-say-shes-stable-509695.html|title=Kanika Kapoor Tests COVID-19 Positive For 5th Time|newspaper=Indiatimes}}</ref> On 4 April, her sixth test came negative for coronavirus.<ref>https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/apr/04/singer-kanika-kapoor-tests-negative-for-coronavirus-in-sixth-report-2125843.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/thelife/news/kanika-kapoor-tests-negative-for-coronavirus-but-shell-have-to-clear-it-one-more-time-just-to-be-sure/articleshow/74984626.cms |title=Kanika Kapoor tests negative for Coronavirus \u2014 but she\u2019ll have to clear it one more time just to be sure &#124; Business Insider India |publisher=Businessinsider.in |date= |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> As of 5 April, there have not been positive cases of the disease reported from the people who were in contact with Kapoor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/amp/news/movies/singer-kanika-kapoor-is-finally-corona-negative-2564851.html|title=Singer Kanika Kapoor is Finally Corona Negative|publisher=News18|date=5 April 2020}}</ref>Following the second negative report for COVID-19 she was discharged from the hospital on 6 April 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/entertainment/singer-kanika-kapoor-discharged-from-hospital-after-testing-negative-for-coronavirus-in-sixth-attemp-2206748%3famp=1&akamai-rum=off|title=Singer Kanika Kapoor Discharged From Hospital After Testing Negative For Coronavirus In Sixth Attempt|work=NDTV|date=6 April 2020}}</ref><ref>https://www.news18.com/news/movies/kanika-kapoor-discahrged-from-hospital-after-testing-negative-for-covid-19-for-2nd-time-2565977.html</ref>\n\n\nKanika Kapoor finally recovers from Covid-19, discharged from hospital; asked to self-isolate at home <ref>{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/kanika-kapoor-finally-recovers-from-covid-19-discharged-from-hospital-asked-to-self-isolate-at-home/articleshow/75005006.cms|title=Kanika Kapoor finally recovers from Covid-19, discharged from hospital; asked to self-isolate at home|work=|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n\n<br />\n==Career==\n[[File:Kanika Kapoor at HT Most Stylish Awards 2016.jpg|left|thumb|165px|Kapoor at the [[Hindustan Times|HT]] Most Stylish Awards 2016]]\nIn 2012, Kapoor released the music video \"[[Alif Allah (Jugni)#Adaption and International Success|Jugni Ji]]\", featuring [[Dr. Zeus]]. The track was the remix version of the Pakistani Sufi song \"[[Alif Allah (Jugni)|Alif Allah]]\", originally sung by [[Arif Lohar]] and [[Meesha Shafi]] at the [[Coke Studio Pakistan (season 3)|third season]] of the musical series ''[[Coke Studio Pakistan]]'' in 2010. Upon the release, \"Jugni Ji\" went on to become one of the biggest singles of 2012 and Kapoor earned the [[Classic Brit Awards|Brit Asia TV Music Award for Best Single]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140913/entertainment-bollywood/article/meet-multi-talented-kanika-kapoor |title=Meet the multi-talented, Kanika Kapoor |newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |author=Sneha K. Sukumar |date=13 September 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> By the success of \"Jugni Ji\", [[Meet Bros Anjjan]] asked Kapoor to sing the song  \"[[Baby Doll (Kanika Kapoor song)|Baby Doll]]\" for the film ''[[Ragini MMS 2]]'' (2014), which marked her [[Bollywood]] singing debut. The song created hype over its release and topped the charts with winning [[Mirchi Music Awards]] for the \"Number One Song of the Year\" award.<ref name=\"toi45522476\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Bollywood-music-report-Jan-Dec-2014/articleshow/45522476.cms |title=Bollywood music report Jan\u2013Dec 2014 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |author=Priya Gupta |date=16 October 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> Kapoor was critically praised for her singing style and went on to win several awards, including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Female Playback Singer]]. The same year she collaborated again with Dr. Zeus along with [[Vishal-Shekhar]] for the song \"Lovely\" in ''[[Happy New Year (2014 film)|Happy New Year]]'' which was picturised on [[Deepika Padukone]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/news/2478601/Kanika-Kapoor-to-sing-in-Happy-New-Year |title=Kanika Kapoor to sing in Happy New Year|work=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |date=21 April 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> The soundtrack of the album also includes a [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] remix of the song titled \"Kamlee\". Both the songs \"Lovely\" and \"Kamlee\" received generally positive reviews and were proved to be a major success.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/moviemicro/musiccriticreview/id/506826 |title=Happy New Year (2014) \u2013 Music Review |work=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |author=Rajiv Vijayakar |date=9 October 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kanika Kapoor at SLAM The Tour.jpg|right|thumb|Kapoor performing at \"SLAM! The Tour\"]]\nThat same year, she participated in a concert tour across North America, entitled \"SLAM! The Tour\", in which she performed alongside [[Shah Rukh Khan]] and [[Deepika Padukone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koimoi.com/videos/srk-madhuri-deepika-sizzle-in-the-new-promo-of-slam-the-tour/ |title=SRK, Madhuri, Deepika Sizzle in the New Promo of SLAM-The Tour  |publisher=[[Koimoi]] |date=1 September 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> Apart from concerts and tours, she has also been signed by an NGO for children, as their brand ambassador, where she promoted the cause of children's education.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Kanika-Kapoor-I-did-not-spend-a-single-penny-in-the-making-of-Baby-Doll/articleshow/38848249.cms |title=Kanika Kapoor: I did not spend a single penny in the making of Baby Doll |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |date=22 July 2014|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> She also relaunched her own fashion brand \"Kanika Kapoor: House of [[Chikan (embroidery)|Chikankari]]\" to help the female artisans in Lucknow and develop this art of embroidery and textile decoration.\n\nIn the year 2015, she collaborated again with Meet Bros Anjjan for the song \"[[Chittiyaan Kalaiyaan]]\" in ''[[Roy (film)|Roy]]'', which became a huge critical and commercial success and was the playback singer for [[Sunny Leone]] in the song \"Desi Look\" in the movie ''[[Ek Paheli Leela]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/roy-chittiyan-kalaiyaan-jacqueline-fernandez-meet-brothers-ranbir-kapoor-arjun-rampal/1/412066.html|title=Roy: Watch Jacqueline Fernandez and Meet Brothers in Chittiyaan Kalaiyaan|work=India Today|date=8 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ek-paheli-leela-watch-sunny-leone-hot-seductive-moves-in-desi-look/1/419991.html|title=Ek Paheli Leela: Watch Sunny Leone's seductive moves in Desi Look|work=[[India Today]]|date=20 February 2015}}</ref> The song was her last collaboration with Zeus and parted ways with him due to his false claim of being the producer and composer of the song \"Baby Doll\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Dr-Zeus-accuses-Baby-Doll-composers-Meet-Brothers-of-plagiarism/articleshow/45667378.cms|title=Dr Zeus accuses 'Baby Doll' composers Meet Brothers of plagiarism|work=The Times of India|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> She collaborated third time with [[Meet Bros Anjjan]] for the song \"Nachan Farrate\" for the movie ''[[All Is Well (2015 film)|All Is Well]]''. She sang \"Neendein Khul Jaati Hain\" for the film ''[[Hate Story 3]]'', collaborating fourth time with [[Meet Bros]].<ref name=\"youtube.com\">{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AuR-Rjx_3qs|title=Neendein Khul Jaati Hain FULL AUDIO Song \u2013 Meet Bros ft. Mika Singh \u2013 Kanika \u2013 Hate Story 3|date=4 November 2015|via=YouTube}}</ref> She also sang a welcome song titled \"Hello Namstey\" for [[India]]'s Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] when he attended a gathering at [[Wembley Stadium]], London on 13 November 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-news-india/modi-in-uk-baby-doll-singer-kanika-kapoor-to-sing-at-wembley-event/|title=Modi in UK: 'Baby Doll' singer Kanika Kapoor to sing at Wembley event|work=[[The Indian Express]]|accessdate=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe regularly arranges and takes part in live shows and concerts. In 2016, she paired up with various composers including [[Amit Trivedi]], [[Raghav Sachar]]. In an interview, she said that she will now concentrate more on [[Sufi music|Sufi]] and classical tracks. She will also release her songs as [[Single (music)|singles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiawest.com/entertainment/interviews/kanika-kapoor-i-am-living-my-ambitions-and-dreams/article_1a70da08-e93b-11e4-aa9c-7f2a83cd8674.html|title=Kanika Kapoor: 'I Am Living My Ambitions and Dreams'|work=India-West|accessdate=22 April 2015|author=R.M. Vijayakar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, she was made brand ambassador of Swiss Watch manufacturer [[88 Rue du Rhone]], an independent brand by Raymond Weil. In 2019, Kapoor was one of the judges of singing reality show ''[[The Voice (Indian season 3)|The Voice]]'' (season 3).<ref>{{cite news |title=Kanika Kapoor to be coach on 'The Voice' |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/kanika-kapoor-to-be-coach-on-the-voice/articleshow/67529909.cms |accessdate=11 February 2019 |newspaper=The Times of India |date=14 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"|\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortab